NAME
       termios - terminal attribute control

SYNOPSIS
       #include <termios.h>

       int tcgetattr(int fd, struct termios *t);
       int tcsetattr(int fd, int actions, const struct termios *t);
       int tcflush(int fd, int queue);
       int tcdrain(int fd);
       int tcflow(int fd, int action);
       int tcsendbreak(int fd, int duration);
       pid_t tcgetsid(int fd);

       void    cfmakeraw(struct termios *t);
       speed_t cfgetispeed(const struct termios *t);
       speed_t cfgetospeed(const struct termios *t);
       int     cfsetispeed(struct termios *t, speed_t s);
       int     cfsetospeed(struct termios *t, speed_t s);
       int     cfsetspeed(struct termios *t, speed_t s);

DESCRIPTION
       libcervus provides a POSIX-compatible termios interface that
       maps to the kernel TTY through the TCGETS, TCSETS, TCSETSW,
       TCSETSF, TCFLSH, TCDRAIN, TCSBRK and TCXONC ioctls.

       The structure is 48 bytes wide and matches the kernel layout:

           tcflag_t c_iflag, c_oflag, c_cflag, c_lflag;
           cc_t     c_cc[NCCS];

       Baud rate is stored in the CBAUD field of c_cflag and accessed
       through cfget/cfsetispeed / ospeed. The constants B0..B38400
       are encoded indices, not the raw bit-rate.

       cfmakeraw() configures *t for fully non-canonical, no-echo,
       no-signal, 8-bit operation with VMIN=1 and VTIME=0.

TTY MODES
       Canonical mode (default): read() returns whole lines; line
       editing follows VERASE / VKILL.

       Non-canonical mode (~ICANON): every byte is delivered as soon
       as it is available. Combine with TIOCSNONBLOCK to make read()
       return -1 / EAGAIN when no data is buffered.

ACTIONS
       The third argument to tcsetattr selects when the change takes
       effect: TCSANOW immediately, TCSADRAIN after draining the
       output queue, TCSAFLUSH also discards input.

       tcflush() empties the input queue (TCIFLUSH), the output queue
       (TCOFLUSH), or both (TCIOFLUSH).

EXAMPLES
       struct termios o, raw;
       tcgetattr(0, &o);
       raw = o;
       cfmakeraw(&raw);
       tcsetattr(0, TCSAFLUSH, &raw);
       /* ... read raw bytes from stdin ... */
       tcsetattr(0, TCSAFLUSH, &o);

SEE ALSO
       read(2), ioctl(2), curses(3)
